==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Loom
<hw>Loom</hw> <pr>(l⟦oomac⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>
<def>See <er>Loon</er>, the bird.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Loom</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Loom
<hw>Loom</hw> <pr>(l⟦oomac⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>lome</ets>, AS. <ets>gel⟦omac⟧ma</ets> utensil,
implement.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A frame or machine of wood or other material, in
which a weaver forms cloth out of thread; a machine for interweaving
yarn or threads into a fabric, as in knitting or lace making.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hector, when he sees Andromache overwhelmed with terror, sends her
for consolation to the <qex>loom</qex> and the distaff.</q>
<rj><qau>Rambler.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>That part of an oar which is near
the grip or handle and inboard from the rowlock.</def>
<rj><au>Totten.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Loom</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Loom
<hw>Loom</hw> <pr>(l⟦oomac⟧m)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Loomed</conjf> <pr>(l⟦oomac⟧md)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Looming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>lumen</ets> to shine, Icel. <ets>ljoma</ets>; akin to AS.
<ets>le⟦iacute⟧ma</ets> light, and E. <ets>light</ets>; or cf. OF.
<ets>lumer</ets> to shine, L. <ets>luminare</ets> to illumine,
<ets>lumen</ets> light; akin to E. <ets>light</ets>. ⟦root⟧122. See
<er>Light</er> not dark.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To appear above the
surface either of sea or land, or to appear enlarged, or distorted and
indistinct, as a distant object, a ship at sea, or a mountain, esp. from
atmospheric influences; <as>as, the ship <ex>looms</ex> large; the land
<ex>looms</ex> high.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Awful she <qex>looms</qex>, the terror of the main.</q>
<rj><qau>H. J. Pye.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To rise and to be eminent; to be elevated or
ennobled, in a moral sense.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On no occasion does he [Paul] <qex>loom</qex> so high, and shine
so gloriously, as in the context.</q> <rj><qau>J. M.
Mason.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To become imminent; to impend.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Loom</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Loom
<hw>Loom</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state of looming; esp., an
unnatural and indistinct appearance of elevation or enlargement of
anything, as of land or of a ship, seen by one at sea.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Loom-gale</ent>⟦br⟧
